ic\" data-return-focus=\"#zDocsTopicActionsMobile\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_main_2531924\" data-toggle=\"modal\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Aug 16, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent wide\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104sdk1665702978293.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/sdk1665702978293.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/sdk1665702978293.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"sdk1665702978293\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n      Referential Integrity Limitations\n </h1>\n<div class=\"body refbody\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">\n</p>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__section_lpn_ydj_kcc\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d357817e54\">Overflow Tables</h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__p_d62639e1_d62640e1_d62641e1\">Only connectors which set\n               <code class=\"ph codeph\">uinfo-&gt;osegm</code> to a non-zero value in the Info call can support\n            referential integrity in the DBMS. When <code class=\"ph codeph\">uinfo-&gt;osegm</code> is set to zero,\n            Uniface uses a concatenated primary key for overflow tables. In that case the\n            relationship between a base table with a compound primary key and its overflow table\n            cannot be maintained by the DBMS.</p>\n</section>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__section_p5b_b2j_kcc\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d357817e69\">Incompatibility Between Uniface Modes and DDL </h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__p_d62645e1_d62646e1_d62647e1\">The SQL used to create the relationships and foreign\n            key rules (Open mode 4) is generated independently from the SQL to create tables (Open\n            mode 2). It is assumed that the relationships and rules can be created by a combination\n            of the following:</p>\n<ol class=\"ol\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__ol_mhx_c2j_kcc\">\n<li class=\"li\"><code class=\"ph codeph\">CREATE TRIGGER</code>\n<var class=\"keyword varname\">TriggerName</var></li>\n<li class=\"li\"><code class=\"ph codeph\">ALTER TABLE</code>\n<var class=\"keyword varname\">TableName</var>\n<code class=\"ph codeph\">ADD CONSTRAINT</code>\n<var class=\"keyword varname\">Constraint</var></li>\n</ol>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__p_d62648e1_d62649e1_d62650e1\">When a particular RDBMS requires that the\n            relationships and foreign key rules are defined as part of the <code class=\"ph codeph\">CREATE\n               TABLE</code> statement, it is not possible to implement referential integrity with\n            the interface described in this book. Similarly it is assumed that the relationships and\n            foreign key rules can be dropped independently.</p>\n</section>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__section_vtj_k2j_kcc\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d357817e107\">ANSI-2 SQL Compliance</h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__p_d62654e1_d62655e1_d62656e1\">ANSI-2 SQL-compliant DBMSs allow a constraint or a\n            trigger to be disabled without it being dropped. In the disabled state, disabling has no\n            semantic effect, but the definition of the constraint or of the trigger is retained in\n            the DBMS dictionary. The following state transition diagram for a single constraint\n            models this functionality:</p>\n<figure class=\"fig fignone\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__fig_d62657e1_d62658e1_d62659e1\">\n<div class=\"p\">\n<figure class=\"fig fignone\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__fig_skz_r2j_kcc\">\n<img alt=\"State transition diagram for a single constraint models\" class=\"image\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__image_tkz_r2j_kcc\" src=\"https://docs-be.rocketsoftware.com/bundle/uniface_104/page/ddcbstdf24.gif?_LANG=enus\"/>\n</figure>\n</div>\n</figure>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"sdk1665702978293__p_d62660e1_d62661e1_d62662e1\">The referential integrity implementation of Uniface\n            supports only the states <code class=\"ph codeph\">CONSTRAINT NONEXISTENT</code> and <code class=\"ph codeph\">CONSTRAINT\n               ENABLED</code>, and supports only the transitions <code class=\"ph codeph\">create constraint\n               enabled</code> and <code class=\"ph codeph\">drop constraint</code>. Supporting the state\n               <code class=\"ph codeph\">CONSTRAINT DISABLED</code> would needlessly introduce complications and\n            RDBMS dependencies (not all DBMSs support disabling constraints or triggers). When using\n            Uniface to manage constraints, do not disable a constraint instead of dropping it, since\n            Uniface regenerates the SQL to create the constraint when it needs to be enabled.</p>\n</section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2531924\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2531924\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Referential Integrity Limitations Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Aug 16, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Referential Integrity Limitations Overflow Tables Only connectors which set uinfo->osegm to a non-zero value in the Info call can support referential integrity in the DBMS. When uinfo->osegm is set to zero, Uniface uses a concatenated primary key for overflow tables. In that case the relationship between a base table with a compound primary key and its overflow table cannot be maintained by the DBMS. Incompatibility Between Uniface Modes and DDL The SQL used to create the relationships and foreign key rules (Open mode 4) is generated independently from the SQL to create tables (Open mode 2). It is assumed that the relationships and rules can be created by a combination of the following: CREATE TRIGGER TriggerName ALTER TABLE TableName ADD CONSTRAINT Constraint When a particular RDBMS requires that the relationships and foreign key rules are defined as part of the CREATE TABLE statement, it is not possible to implement referential integrity with the interface described in this book. Similarly it is assumed that the relationships and foreign key rules can be dropped independently. ANSI-2 SQL Compliance ANSI-2 SQL-compliant DBMSs allow a constraint or a trigger to be disabled without it being dropped. In the disabled state, disabling has no semantic effect, but the definition of the constraint or of the trigger is retained in the DBMS dictionary. The following state transition diagram for a single constraint models this functionality: The referential integrity implementation of Uniface supports only the states CONSTRAINT NONEXISTENT and CONSTRAINT ENABLED , and supports only the transitions create constraint enabled and drop constraint . Supporting the state CONSTRAINT DISABLED would needlessly introduce complications and RDBMS dependencies (not all DBMSs support disabling constraints or triggers). When using Uniface to manage constraints, do not disable a constraint instead of dropping it, since Uniface regenerates the SQL to create the constraint when it needs to be enabled. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}